 memoir of Cohen written by the volume editor, Jonathan Wolff, who was a student of Cohen's. A hallmark of the lectures is Cohen's engagement with the thinkers he discusses. Rather than simply trying to render their thought accessible to the modern reader, he tests whether their arguments and positions are clear, sound, and free from contradiction. Throughout, he homes in on central issues and provides fresh approaches to the philosophers he examines. Ultimately, these lectures teach us not only about some of the great thinkers in the history of moral and political philosophy, but also about one of the great thinkers of our time: Cohen himself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEthicsxHistory. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophyxHistory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aAbsolute Idealism.  aAllen W. Wood.  aAristotle.  aBeyond Good and Evil.  aChristine Korsgaard.  aDavid Hume.  aFriedrich Nietzsche.  aG. A. Cohen.  aG. W. F. Hegel.  aImmanuel Kant.  aJewishness.  aJohn Locke.  aJon Elster.  aKarl Marx.  aLeviathan.  aMarxism.  aPhenomenology of Spirit.  aPlato.  aReinhold Niebuhr.  aRepublic.  aRichard Peters.  aSecond Treatise of Government.  aSocrates.  aSophism.  aSoviet Communism.  aThe Genealogy of Morals.  aThe Holy Family.  aTheory of History.  aThomas Hobbes.  aalienation.  aanalytical philosophy.  aauthoritarianism.  aauthority.  abourgeoisie.  acapitalism.  acapitalist society.  acapitalist.  acompetition.  aconsent.  aconvention.  adiffidence.  aequality.  aethics.  aevil.  afaith.  afreedom.  afunctional explanation.  agame theory.  aglory.  agood.  agovernment.  agovernmental authority.  ahealth.  ahistorical materialism.  ahuman essence.  ahuman nature.  ahumanity.  ajust